    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York 144 Thompson St</placeName></p>
			<p rend="aling(right)"><date>March 21<hi rend="sup">st</hi> 5613. 1853</date></p>
			<p>Dear Sir&#47;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">The sealed enclosure addressed to you<lb/> my Brother brought from <placeName>California</placeName> and<lb/> the German paper is an extract from a<lb/> Letter recd by a resident of <placeName>New York</placeName><lb/> it was given to me by a very respectable<lb/> and truthful man who wishes you to translate<lb/> and insert it the &#8220;Occident&#8221; I believe<lb/> there is much truth in what is said<lb/> concerning the <add>Hebrew</add> but of course you<lb/> will exercise your own discretion&#8212;<lb/> wishing you every happiness you yourself<lb/> desire&#160;&#160;I am yours faithfully</p>
			<p><persName role="author">Ansel Leo</persName></p>
			<p>To</p>
			<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p><placeName>371&#8212;Walnut St</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
			<p><add>&#63;</add> <persName>Adolph Back</persName></p>
			<p><placeName>275 William st&#58;</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>N. Y.</placeName></p>
		<pb n="4"/>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><add><hi rend="underline">Yiddish</hi></add></p>
			<p>copy</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">My dear friend <persName>Herr Bach</persName>&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">Large orders for Tifillin and Mazuzot<lb/> come over from there&#42;&#44; and people send out such as are<lb/> for the most part improper. The leather for the<lb/> thongs of the T&#39;fillin is bought here form such<lb/> animals which are forbidden in the Torah. In<lb/> the same way&#44; they make the cases for the T&#39;fillin<lb/> for head and arm in an improper manner. Much<lb/> less can the Parashoth contained in them be<lb/> Kosher since the scribe has them printed and<lb/> sells a complete pair of T&#39;fillin for 6 or 6 &#189;<lb/> groshen. Therefore&#44; I think it would be a great<lb/> &#8220;Mitzva&#8221; to have it announced there among the<lb/> pious and whole hearted that whatever T&#39;fillin and<lb/> Mezuzot arrive there&#44; without the seal of a legi&#45;<lb/>timate court&#44; should not be accepted as Kosher&#44;<lb/> and that a legitimate court will take care that<lb/> T&#39;fillin and Mezuzot as well as Torahs should be sent<lb/> out in a Kosher fashion.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Your friend who blesses you and<lb/> your house with all good</p>
          <p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">David Schlesinger</persName></p>
          <p rend="indent(6)">Dayyau of <placeName>Breslau</placeName></p>
			<p>&#42;<placeName>America</placeName>&#44; presumably</p>
			<p>&#8220;Judge&#8221;</p>
          
        </body>
